  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Use \"above-phenomenal\" to preserve 形/形而上 structure",
    "content": "1. Yes, this is a significant loss. The passage's argument depends on the reader seeing that 形而上 structurally contains 形 — that the \"metaphysical\" is defined relationally as \"above the phenomenal,\" not as a separate category. Without this, the English reader gets a binary opposition (metaphysical vs. phenomenal) but misses that one term is literally built from the other. The philosophical point — that the metaphysical is not a separate realm but a structural position relative to form — disappears.\n\n2. A TN is the minimum. But I think we can do better.\n\n3. Consider rendering it as: \"Thus the Way is the highest — it is the above-phenomenal (形而上, xing er shang) — while ritual conduct is the lowest — it is the phenomenal (形, xing) itself.\"\n\n\"Above-phenomenal\" is ugly but it does exactly what the Chinese does: it visibly contains \"phenomenal\" within itself, so the reader can see the structural relationship. A TN can then explain: \"The Chinese term 形而上 (conventionally translated 'metaphysical') literally means 'above form/the phenomenal' (形 + 而上). The author exploits this internal structure: 道 is 形而上 (above the phenomenal) while 礼 is 形 (the phenomenal itself). We render 形而上 as 'above-phenomenal' to preserve this etymological relationship, which is load-bearing in the argument.\"\n\nThis follows the same principle as 現象X — if the internal structure of a term is doing philosophical work, the translation must make that structure visible. \"Metaphysical\" hides it; \"above-phenomenal\" shows it."
  }
}
